snippet.textDisplay:
@$ - 100 years ago (1918) we (the US) first made public issue $500, $1000, $5000, and $10000 bills that were put in standard circulation. In 1969 they stopped making them because they weren't being used that frequently - so basically they were being printed for nothing. Nowadays if a bank receives one, they must send it for destruction.
It's pretty ironic though, I remember in the 90s my father getting paid in $500's and $1000's sometimes and inflation will only continue to increase - now they're needed more than ever. Hell a McDonalds job in my state will net you $1376 a month at minimum wage or say $1100 after taxes. This is not a good case for $500 and $1000 bills but it goes to show where we are headed. Even with digital currency being the main payment platform, it makes sense for physical currency to keep up as needed.
